entry.content:
Adds a general utility method to ObservingAppAgent to allow retrieving

the agent if it's already been created; this is symmetrical with

Existing AppStateAgents that don't subclass ObservingAppAgent can be trivially converted (assuming they are at least also AppSateObservers).

> [PWA] Refactoring state machine into AppBannerManager.

>

> This CL is the next incremental step into removing all of the

> inheritance in the AppBannerManager system. It does this by:

> - Move state mutation back into base class - e.g. stop calling

> UpdateState, stop making AppBannerManager member function calls, and

> stop other AppBannerManager member variable modification.

entry.title: [infra] Update the format of keys used when not specifying an ID.
entry.content:
Currently for an unscoped node type with allow_empty_id=True, if a key

ID isn't specified the nodes library creates a key where the ID value

for the _CHROMIUM_NS is set to "UNIQUE", which prevents collisions if

the generated sequence value is the same as an explicitly provided ID

value. However, this means that there could be collisions if the node

type's kind is used as the scoped node type:



Example using bundles and per-test modifications:



key for anonymous bundle with ID generated as "1"

[("@chromium", "UNIQUE"), ("targets|bundle", "1")]

key for bundle with name "1"

[("@chromium", ""), ("targets|bundle", "1")]



key for modification to test foo in anonymous bundle

[("@chromium", ""), ("targets|bundle", "1"), ("targets|test", "foo")]

key for modification to test foo in bundle 1

[("@chromium", ""), ("targets|bundle", "1"), ("targets|test", "foo")]



While it us unlikely that someone would define an entity with an

entirely numeric name, it's not impossible and the use of an entirely

numeric ID for unname entities can produce confusing error messages.



To address the possibility of conflicts and improve error messages for

nodes using a generated ID, this changes the code to instead append the

number to a prefix that clearly identifies an unnamed declaration. When

explicitly specifying a key ID, it cannot begin with the prefix used for

anonymous IDs.

entry.title: Fenced frames: DisableUntrustedNetwork applies to shared workers
entry.content:
We already get this from the partition nonce work that was done

previously. This CL adds a WPT to confirm that the partition nonce

network disabling also works for shared workers created by fenced

frames.



This CL also adds a test to confirm that a shared worker cannot be used

to postMessage() across a fenced boundary. We already get this behavior

because a fenced frame is treated as being cross-origin, which means the

shared worker will not be shared across fenced frame boundaries, even if

being loaded in a document that is same-origin to the fenced frame.
